{
  "doc_id": "15394",
  "text": "Many such mechanisms have been discovered [CITATION_1] , but one potential mechanism that has yet to be examined is vesicular zinc. \"Vesicular zinc\" refers to zinc ions that are sequestered in the synaptic vesicles of neurons -in the forebrain, zinc is found in a subset of glutamatergic neurons [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This zinc is released in an activity-dependent manner and can modulate a plethora of targets, including glutamate receptors [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Notably, vesicular zinc storage is the responsibility of a protein called zinc transporter 3 (ZnT3; [CITATION_8] Wenzel et al., 1997) , encoded by the SLC30A3 gene. When this transporter is eliminated, as in the ZnT3 knockout (KO) mouse, vesicular zinc can no longer be detected [CITATION_9] , providing a useful tool with which to study the function of vesicular zinc in the brain.",
